# Materials Engineering Research

## Overview

My research in Materials Engineering spans more than three decades, combining metallurgy, industrial process engineering, experimental investigation, and computational modeling.

The trajectory began with studies on the hot mechanical behavior of metallic materials, thermomechanical processing, and dynamic recrystallization. It subsequently expanded toward industrial metallurgical processes, silicon metal production and refining, hydrometallurgy, microstructural evolution, cementitious materials, and nanomaterials.

A recurring characteristic of this work is the connection between engineering phenomena, quantitative analysis, and modeling. More recently, this trajectory has evolved toward three-dimensional computational simulation of microstructural phenomena and advanced materials research.

---

## Hot Deformation and Thermomechanical Processing

Early research focused on the mechanical behavior of metallic materials under hot deformation conditions.

Studies addressed aluminum alloys, titanium, and Ti-6Al-4V, with emphasis on stress-strain behavior, axial compression, and the response of metallic materials at elevated temperatures.

This research established an early connection between physical metallurgy, mechanical behavior, and quantitative interpretation of deformation phenomena.

---

## Dynamic Recrystallization and Steel Processing

A major early research line investigated dynamic recrystallization during the hot working of steels.

The studies explored the use of stress-strain curve modeling to identify and analyze the occurrence of dynamic recrystallization during hot rolling.

This work represents an important foundation for my later interest in computational descriptions of microstructural evolution. Decades later, this research trajectory would extend toward three-dimensional cellular automata and the development of the SimCres computational framework.

---

## Industrial Metallurgy and Silicon Metal Processing

My industrial metallurgical research included direct involvement with silicon metal production and refining processes.

The work addressed raw material control, refining operations, synthetic slag models, and optimization of sampling procedures for refined liquid silicon metal. Several of these investigations were developed in connection with industrial production at the Eletrosilex plant and presented at national and international metallurgical conferences.

These studies reflect a strongly applied phase of my engineering career, in which process control, metallurgical modeling, sampling methodology, and industrial production problems were investigated in an operational environment.

---

## Hydrometallurgy and Industrial Process Engineering

Research in hydrometallurgy addressed the treatment and valorization of steel pickling liquors.

A microwave-hydrothermal process was investigated for the simultaneous production of impurity-free water and magnetite from industrial steel pickling solutions.

This work extended my research toward industrial residue processing, aqueous metallurgical systems, and the development of engineering routes for material recovery and process sustainability.

---

## Cementitious Materials and Nanomaterials

Current research activities also include cementitious materials and nanomaterials.

Recent investigations address the incorporation of carbon nanotubes into cement-based materials and the resulting effects on material behavior and performance.

This research expands my Materials Engineering activities toward advanced construction materials and nanoscale modification of engineering materials.

---

## Computational Microstructure Modeling

My earlier work on deformation, recrystallization, and microstructural phenomena progressively converged with mathematical and computational modeling.

This trajectory led to the development of **SimCres**, a computational framework based on three-dimensional cellular automata for the simulation and quantitative analysis of microstructural evolution.

The current research cycle includes grain growth, recrystallization-related phenomena, three-dimensional morphology, surface-area measurement, boundary effects, and computational characterization of evolving microstructures.

